<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>This may sound trite, but it's easy if you stay single.  When I graduated college (in the middle of the dot com bust), I made $30k at my first programming job.  I lived in a cheap ($525/mo) apartment in Houston and drove a used car which was paid off.  Not only was I able to live comfortably (see a movie, buy a cd or eat out whenever I felt like it), I was also able to pay off my student loans at an accelerated rate of $500/mo.  Subtracting just the student loan payments would have put me at an equivalent salary of $24k.<p>That being said, I can't imagine raising kids on that wage.</font></span><p><font size=1><font color=#f6f6ef>-----</font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table border=0><tr><td><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/s.gif" height=1 width=200></td><td valign=top><center><a id=up_2981598 href="vote?for=2981598&dir=up&whence=%2f%78%3f%66%6e%69%64%3d%75%53%63%4f%31%65%68%56%50%4b"><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/grayarrow.gif" border=0 vspace=3 hspace=2></a><span id=down_2981598></span></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px; "><span class="comhead"><a href="user?id=_delirium">_delirium</a> 146 days ago  | <a href="item?id=2981598">link</a></span></div><br>
